div.div:
The removal of chlorine was investigated using CNT-coated PES membranes during single-pass flow-through filtration (

 Figure


 1

). The relative difference in the free chlorine in the permeate as compared to the feed was measured as a function of the filtrate volume. CNT membranes (i.e., CNTs coated on the PES support membrane) effectively removed chlorine while simultaneously filtering feed water. In contrast, pristine PES membranes (without CNT coatings) exhibited a negligible difference in chlorine concentration between the feed and permeate, indicating an insignificant effect of PES membranes on chlorine removal. This result was expected as PES membranes were porous (average pore diameter, 0.03 μm), and PES surface adsorption was expected to be negligible. The significant capability of removing chlorine by CNTs was also confirmed in experiments that were conducted using batch reactors with CNTs dispersed in DI water containing chlorine (Figure S2 in the

 Supporting Information

). At the initial stage of filtration (first 5–10 mL), the CNT membranes were highly effective, achieving approximately 80% chlorine removal, resulting in a greatly reduced concentration of chlorine in the permeate. However, the concentration of chlorine in the permeate continuously increased over the course of filtering 200 mL of chlorinated water, indicating the gradual saturation of active sites in CNT membranes.

